                                                                                                               State Bank puts up a stellar show
          OUR BUREAU                          Good going                                  
	Mumbai, Jan. 24: Buoyed by a robust growth in its corporate, SME and retail advances, along with a sharp jump in net interest income, the State Bank of India has clocked a 52 per cent jump in consolidated third-quarter net profit at Rs 3,713.66 crore against Rs 2,442.32 crore in the year-ago period.        
	The state-run bank, which along with its associates controls a quarter of Indias loans and deposits, said its total income rose to Rs 30,318.14 crore, up 24 per cent from Rs 24,380.99 crore in the year-ago period.        
	The lenders net non-performing assets shrunk to 1.36 per cent during the quarter from 1.44 per cent a year back. Gross NPAs also contracted to 2.61 per cent from 2.82 per cent a year ago, the release said.        
	During the quarter, the banks total advances grew by Rs 1,14,265 crore, up 28.85 per cent from Rs 3,96,014 crore in the same period last year.         
	The advances were boosted by a 47 per cent jump in large corporate loans and a 28 per cent rise in SME advances, the SBI said.        
	Its home-loan portfolio swelled 22 per cent in the quarter, while retail, agriculture and mid-corporate portfolios jumped by 27, 26 and 23 per cent, respectively.        
	The bank also witnessed a 32 per cent growth in its auto loans and an impressive 47 per cent jump in educational loans during the quarter. On a year-on-year basis, the SBIs international advances grew 33 per cent during the period.         
	The SBIs net interest income leapt by 35 per cent in the third quarter to Rs 5,758 crore from Rs 4,256 crore in the same quarter of the previous financial year.        
	The SBIs combined deposits in current accounts and savings accounts jumped to Rs 2,37,307 crore, up 21 per cent, from Rs 1,95,796 crore in the corresponding period of the last financial year, the bank said.        
	At present, the SBI has a deposit base of Rs 6,92,921 crore, which grew by 36 per cent during the quarter, compared with Rs 5,10,132 crore in the corresponding quarter last year.        
	State Bank, which has 11,000 branches across India and abroad, has the lowest cost of funds among the nations lenders.        
	The bulk of its funds come from savings bank deposits that carry a cost of 3.5 percent in annual interest payments, compared with 12.25 percent the bank charges on loans to its best clients.        
	Shares of the State Bank, which the market values at about $13.5 billion, shed 12 percent in the December quarter, less than the 25 per cent fall in the sensex and the 16 per cent drop in the sector index.        
	The shares ended 4.3 percent lower at Rs 1,041.75 on the BSE on Friday.                                                                                                                                        
